[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    648[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    649[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    650[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    651[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Gap Between This and Production
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    652[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    653[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This example works. Run it and you'll get a ranked list of rising-risk patients with trajectory metrics and severity tiers. But there's a meaningful distance between "works in a script" and "runs monthly on a 500K-member population with real clinical data." Here's where that gap lives:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    654[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    655[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Distributed processing.** This example loops through patients sequentially. For a 500K-member population with 24 months of history, that's millions of score records. Production uses AWS Glue (Spark-based) to parallelize trajectory computation across the population. Each patient's trajectory is independent, making this embarrassingly parallel, but you need the distributed infrastructure to handle the scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    656[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    657[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real risk model integration.** We generate synthetic scores here. In production, Step 1 is a SageMaker batch transform job that scores the entire population through your trained risk model (typically XGBoost or a gradient boosted tree trained on claims + clinical features). The model itself needs periodic retraining, and when you retrain, you need to either re-score the full history with the new model or maintain version-specific baselines. Score comparisons across model versions are meaningless.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    658[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    659[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Score versioning.** This is the single biggest operational headache. If your risk model changes (retrained, new features, new target definition), historical scores are no longer comparable to current scores. A patient whose score went from 0.3 to 0.5 might have genuinely deteriorated, or the new model might just score everyone higher. Production systems either re-score all history with the current model (expensive but clean) or maintain version-specific percentile baselines (cheaper but more complex).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    660[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    661[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Error handling and retries.** Every AWS API call can fail. Glue jobs can timeout. SageMaker batch transforms can produce partial results. DynamoDB writes can be throttled. Production wraps every external call in retry logic with exponential backoff and dead-letter queues for persistent failures. A single patient's trajectory computation failure should not crash the entire pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    662[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    663[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Input validation.** This code trusts its inputs. Production validates that score histories are within expected ranges, that dates are monotonically increasing, that patient IDs match the enrollment roster, and that the feature matrix has the expected schema. Garbage in, garbage out is especially dangerous when the output drives clinical interventions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    664[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    665[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stale data detection.** A patient who hasn't had a visit in 12 months will have a flat trajectory (no new scores). But their actual risk might be increasing silently. Production systems flag patients with stale data for outreach, independent of the trajectory model. This is a separate process that checks "when was the last time we had fresh clinical data for this patient?" and escalates if the gap exceeds a threshold.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    666[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    667[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Threshold calibration feedback loop.** The thresholds in this example are hardcoded. Production systems include a feedback mechanism where care managers mark flags as "appropriate" or "not actionable." That signal feeds back into threshold tuning. Without this loop, you're guessing at the right sensitivity/specificity tradeoff.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    668[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    669[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IAM least-privilege.** The IAM role for this pipeline should have exactly the permissions it needs: `s3:GetObject` scoped to the score history bucket, `dynamodb:PutItem` scoped to the risk state table, `events:PutEvents` scoped to the specific event bus. Not `s3:*`. Not `AdministratorAccess`.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    670[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    671[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **VPC and network isolation.** In production, Glue jobs and Lambda functions run inside a VPC with private subnets and VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, and EventBridge. Risk scores are derived from PHI. They should never traverse the public internet.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    672[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    673[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Encryption.** All S3 buckets use SSE-KMS with customer-managed keys. DynamoDB uses encryption at rest. All API calls use TLS. KMS key policies restrict access to the pipeline's execution roles only.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    674[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    675[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Monitoring and alerting.** Production pipelines emit CloudWatch metrics for: pipeline runtime, patients scored, patients flagged, flag rate (as a percentage of population), and any errors. Anomaly detection on the flag rate catches model drift (if you suddenly flag 10% of the population instead of the usual 1%, something is wrong with the model or the data).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    676[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    677[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **DynamoDB Decimal handling.** DynamoDB's resource layer rejects raw Python floats. This example converts to Decimal explicitly, but any new numeric field you add must also be converted. The `boto3` DynamoDB resource will raise a `TypeError` on any raw float in a `put_item` call. This is mentioned in the code but worth repeating: it will bite you if you forget.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    678[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    679[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regression to the mean.** Roughly 30-50% of patients flagged as "rising risk" would have stabilized without intervention. Measuring true intervention effectiveness requires either a randomized holdout (ethically complex in healthcare) or sophisticated observational methods (propensity score matching, difference-in-differences). Without this, you cannot distinguish "our intervention worked" from "the patient would have gotten better anyway."
